  , issueTitle =
      "Dramatically slower union performance with map vs merge (queries and changefeeds)"
  , issuePullRequest = Nothing
  , issueUrl =
      "https://api.github.com/repos/rethinkdb/rethinkdb/issues/4531"
  , issueCreatedAt = 2015 (-07) (-13) 16 : 18 : 54 UTC
  , issueBody =
      Just
        "I wanted to combine the result of querying three tables into one stream, so I used a union and mapped each result (to add a type field). I had a function to generate the query; here is what it looked like:\n\n```\nfunction userQuery(userId, limit) {\n\n    var predictionQuery    = r.db('demomodel').table('prediction').getAll(userId, {index: 'uid'});\n    var featuresQuery      = r.db('demomodel').table('features').getAll(userId, {index: 'uid'});\n    var rawDataSensorQuery = r.db('demomodel').table('rawdata_sensor').getAll(userId, {index: 'uid'});\n\n    if (limit) {\n        log(\"beginning userQuery for user \" + userId + \" with limit of \" + limit);\n        predictionQuery = predictionQuery.limit(limit);\n        featuresQuery = featuresQuery.limit(limit);\n        rawDataSensorQuery = rawDataSensorQuery.limit(limit);\n    } else {\n        log(\"no limit userQuery for user \" + userId);\n    }\n\n    return predictionQuery.map(as('prediction'))\n        .union(featuresQuery.map(as('features')))\n        .union(rawDataSensorQuery.map(as('rawdata_sensor')));\n\n    function as(s) {\n        return function(n) {\n            return {\n                type: s,\n                data: n\n            }\n        }\n    }\n}\n```\n\nThis would work fine as an individual query, even when I had multiple clients triggering it. The second I created a changefeed with it, though, the queries would slow down dramatically.\n\nWhen I changed the query to use `merge()` instead, the performance became much, much better:\n\n```\nfunction userQuery(userId, limit) {\n\n    var predictionQuery    = r.db('demomodel').table('prediction').filter({uid: userId});\n    var featuresQuery      = r.db('demomodel').table('features').filter({uid: userId});\n    var rawDataSensorQuery = r.db('demomodel').table('rawdata_sensor').filter({uid: userId});\n\n    if (limit) {\n        console.log(\"beginning userQuery for user \" + userId + \" with limit of \" + limit);\n        predictionQuery = predictionQuery.limit(limit);\n        featuresQuery = featuresQuery.limit(limit);\n        rawDataSensorQuery = rawDataSensorQuery.limit(limit);\n    } else {\n        console.log(\"no limit userQuery for user \" + userId);\n    }\n\n    predictionQuery = predictionQuery.merge({ type: 'prediction' });\n    featuresQuery = featuresQuery.merge({ type: 'features' });\n    rawDataSensorQuery = rawDataSensorQuery.merge({ type: 'rawdata_sensor'});\n\n    return predictionQuery\n        .union(featuresQuery)\n        .union(rawDataSensorQuery);\n}\n```\n\nThat runs as expected: multiple clients, changefeeds, queries -- the whole lot.\n\nAny ideas why `map()` would handle so much worse than `merge()` in this case? Is it a bug, or just an underlying limitation based on the way `map()` works?\n"
